  </div>
</section>

<section id="intro">
  <div class="section-tag">The Story Behind the Data</div>
  <div class="personal-badge">🏄 An Athlete's Perspective</div>
  <h2 class="intro-pull reveal">I didn't just study Olympians.<br><em>I was one.</em></h2>
  <div class="intro-body reveal">
    <p>When I first encountered this dataset — 120 years of Olympic history, 70,000 athlete records, spanning Athens 1896 to Rio 2016 — it wasn't just numbers. It was <strong>a world I had lived in</strong>. As a former World Champion windsurfer and a competitive athlete who understands the weight of Olympic ambition, I saw something most data scientists don't: the story of the body behind the performance.</p>
    <p>This investigation is personal. When I analyze age distribution, I'm thinking about when <em>I</em> peaked. When I look at windsurfing weight profiles, I'm thinking about how every kilogram on a board affects speed and stability. This is what makes data science powerful — when the analyst has lived the data.</p>
    <p>I chose the <strong>"120 Years of Olympic History: Athletes and Results"</strong> dataset from Kaggle precisely because it would allow me to ask questions that only an athlete can ask — and answer them with the rigor of a data scientist.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="dataset-card reveal">
    <div><div class="dcard-num">70,000</div><div class="dcard-label">Rows (athlete entries)</div></div>
    <div><div class="dcard-num">15</div><div class="dcard-label">Columns (variables)</div></div>
    <div><div class="dcard-num">1896–2016</div><div class="dcard-label">Years covered</div></div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="insights">
  <div class="insights-header reveal">
    <div class="section-tag" style="justify-content:center;">The Investigation</div>
    <h2 class="insights-title">Four <em>Detective</em> Findings</h2>
    <p class="insights-desc">Interactive charts reproduced from the original Python / Seaborn analysis. Hover to explore the data.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- INSIGHT 1 -->
  <div class="insight-block reveal">
    <div class="insight-text">
      <div class="insight-num">01</div>
      <div class="insight-tag">Age Distribution · displot</div>
      <h3 class="insight-headline">The Olympic Peak: Greatness Arrives Between 21 and 26</h3>
      <div class="insight-body">
        <p>When I plotted the age distribution across all 70,000 records, one thing jumped out immediately: a <strong>sharp, right-skewed bell curve</strong> peaking in the early-to-mid twenties.</p>
        <p>The vast majority of Olympic athletes compete within a narrow window — roughly <strong>ages 21 to 26</strong>. This reflects the biological "sweet spot" where explosive power, neuromuscular coordination, and peak VO₂ max converge.</p>
        <p>The right skew tells a secondary story: a remarkable cohort competes well into their 30s and 40s — testament to the power of experience and technique over raw physical capacity in certain disciplines.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-finding">
        <div class="insight-finding-label">Athlete's Interpretation</div>
        <p>"At 21, I could push harder than ever. By 26, I knew exactly how to push smarter. That's the window the data confirms."</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight-viz">
      <div class="viz-card">
        <div class="viz-title">Age Distribution of Olympic Athletes (1896–2016)</div>
        <div id="chart-age"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- INSIGHT 2 -->
  <div class="insight-block reverse reveal">
    <div class="insight-text">
      <div class="insight-num">02</div>
      <div class="insight-tag">Trend Over Time · lineplot</div>
      <h3 class="insight-headline">The Golden Age: Champions' Peak Has Barely Moved in a Century</h3>
      <div class="insight-body">
        <p>I filtered to <strong>Gold Medalists only</strong>, then plotted their average age across every Olympic year from 1896 to 2016. The result was striking — a remarkably stable band between <strong>23 and 27 years</strong>.</p>
        <p>Despite 120 years of revolutions in sports science, nutrition, and recovery technology, the biological peak for Olympic gold has barely moved. Mid-twenties humans have always been the world's best athletes — and still are.</p>
        <p>However, a <strong>slight upward drift in recent decades</strong> is visible. Modern sports medicine has extended the competitive window, allowing athletes to maintain elite performance longer than their historical counterparts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-finding">
        <div class="insight-finding-label">Statistical Note</div>
        <p>The shaded confidence band represents ±1 standard error. The stability of the mean across 120 years suggests a deep biological constraint on human athletic achievement.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight-viz">
      <div class="viz-card">
        <div class="viz-title">Average Age of Gold Medalists by Olympic Year</div>
        <div id="chart-golden"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- INSIGHT 3 -->
  <div class="insight-block reveal">
    <div class="insight-text">
      <div class="insight-num">03</div>
      <div class="insight-tag">Sport Physiology · boxplot</div>
      <h3 class="insight-headline">Every Kilogram Counts: Windsurfing vs. Basketball</h3>
      <div class="insight-body">
        <p>This insight is the most personal one. As a windsurfer, I know that <strong>body weight is not just a physical attribute — it's a technical variable</strong>. Your relationship with the board, the wind, and the water changes with every kilogram.</p>
        <p>By isolating "Windsurfing" from the broader "Sailing" category (a key data manipulation step), I compared its weight profile against Basketball. The boxplot reveals: <strong>Windsurfers cluster tightly in a narrow band</strong>, while Basketball players show a much wider, heavier distribution.</p>
        <p>This reflects the physics. A heavier body in windsurfing creates drag and disrupts board balance. Basketball accommodates diverse body types for different court roles — point guards to centers.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-finding">
        <div class="insight-finding-label">The Power of Filtering</div>
        <p>Isolating "Windsurfing" from general "Sailing" was critical. Without this step, the insight would have been lost in the noise of heavier sailing disciplines.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight-viz">
      <div class="viz-card">
        <div class="viz-title" style="margin-bottom:8px;">Weight Distribution by Sport (kg)</div>
        <div class="chart-toggle">
          <button class="toggle-btn active" onclick="toggleWeight('both')">Both Sports</button>
          <button class="toggle-btn" onclick="toggleWeight('windsurf')">Windsurfing Only</button>
          <button class="toggle-btn" onclick="toggleWeight('basketball')">Basketball Only</button>
        </div>
        <div id="chart-weight"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- INSIGHT 4 -->
  <div class="insight-block reverse reveal">
    <div class="insight-text">
      <div class="insight-num">04</div>
      <div class="insight-tag">Correlation · relplot / scatterplot</div>
      <h3 class="insight-headline">The Outliers: Olympic Diversity Hidden in a Scatter Plot</h3>
      <div class="insight-body">
        <p>The final investigation asked: what is the relationship between height and weight across all 70,000 athletes, and what do the <strong>outliers tell us</strong>?</p>
        <p>There is a strong positive correlation — taller athletes tend to weigh more. But the scatter plot's power lies in its extremes: athletes far from the trend line, either exceptionally heavy for their height (powerlifters, wrestlers) or remarkably light (gymnasts, windsurfers).</p>
        <p>These outliers are not errors. They are the Olympic ideal — humans who have pushed physiology to its limits in opposite directions, each perfectly optimized for their specific discipline.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-finding">
        <div class="insight-finding-label">Hover to Explore</div>
        <p>Mouse over data points to see individual height and weight values. Note the extreme outlier clusters at the top (heavy lifters) and bottom-right (tall, lean athletes).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight-viz">
      <div class="viz-card">
        <div class="viz-title">Height vs. Weight — All Olympic Athletes</div>
        <div id="chart-scatter"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="summary">
  <div class="section-tag reveal">Conclusions</div>
  <h2 class="summary-title reveal">What 120 Years of Data <em>Taught Me</em></h2>
  <p class="summary-lead reveal">"This investigation proved that data, when read with lived experience, speaks more clearly than numbers alone ever could."</p>
  <div class="summary-findings reveal">
    <div class="summary-item">
      <div class="summary-icon">⏱️</div>
      <div><div class="summary-item-title">The body has a biological clock for greatness</div><div class="summary-item-text">The Olympic peak window of 21–26 is a biological reality, consistent across 120 years of elite competition. Peak physical power and neuromuscular coordination converge in the mid-twenties.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="summary-item">
      <div class="summary-icon">🥇</div>
      <div><div class="summary-item-title">Champions' age is shockingly stable across history</div><div class="summary-item-text">Despite massive advances in sports science, the average gold medalist age has remained between 23–27 since 1896. Biology, not technology, ultimately sets the ceiling — though modern medicine has begun nudging it slightly higher.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="summary-item">
      <div class="summary-icon">⚖️</div>
